00:45:34.028 --> 00:45:36.021
DOUGLAS STONE: That was crazy.

00:45:36.021 --> 00:45:37.770
AUDIENCE: So thank you
so much for coming.

00:45:37.770 --> 00:45:40.540
I really liked your talk
about different dimensions,

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:43.366
like the baseline, swings,
sustain, and recovery.

00:45:43.366 --> 00:45:45.490
It's really good to know
that people are different.

00:45:45.490 --> 00:45:47.370
And I'm different
from anyone else.

00:45:47.370 --> 00:45:47.640
SHEILA HEEN: Yeah.

00:45:47.640 --> 00:45:47.930
DOUGLAS STONE: Yeah.

00:45:47.930 --> 00:45:50.429
AUDIENCE: But I will be very
curious to know whether there's

00:45:50.429 --> 00:45:52.200
like a questionnaire
or like a quiz

00:45:52.200 --> 00:45:56.390
that I can know what like
quandrantile I fall into.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:58.510
Because it's good to know
this, but I don't know,

00:45:58.510 --> 00:46:02.230
like, what is my own standard
compared to other people.

00:46:02.230 --> 00:46:04.230
SHEILA HEEN: Yeah,
so this research

00:46:04.230 --> 00:46:06.860
is actually pulling from
several different researchers.

00:46:06.860 --> 00:46:08.380
So there isn't one
researcher that

00:46:08.380 --> 00:46:12.860
has a questionnaire that
covers all the aspects of this.

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:16.030
Richard Davidson has a
book called "The Emotional

00:46:16.030 --> 00:46:18.510
Life of Your Brain"
that's really interesting

00:46:18.510 --> 00:46:19.930
and is worth reading.

00:46:19.930 --> 00:46:21.932
And he looks at the fact
that positive feeling

00:46:21.932 --> 00:46:24.140
and negative feeling is
processed on different sides.

00:46:24.140 --> 00:46:25.830
And he has a couple
of questionnaires

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:30.130
that are more about life
than about work and feedback

00:46:30.130 --> 00:46:32.960
specifically, how you respond
to events in life that

00:46:32.960 --> 00:46:34.760
may be helpful.

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:37.650
But he also says
check your answers

00:46:37.650 --> 00:46:40.310
against people who know you, OK?

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:42.540
Because you may
think actually I'm

00:46:42.540 --> 00:46:46.190
not still upset about that
guy who cut me off on the road

00:46:46.190 --> 00:46:48.690
or what happened at the
meeting this morning.

00:46:48.690 --> 00:46:50.760
Other people around
you can tell it's still

00:46:50.760 --> 00:46:54.060
affecting the way that you
are interacting with everybody

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:59.462
else, but you're not
necessarily self-aware of that.

00:46:59.462 --> 00:47:00.920
It's one of the
reasons why we need

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:03.620
other people to see ourselves.

00:47:03.620 --> 00:47:05.775
When you ask other
people for feedback--

00:47:05.775 --> 00:47:08.150
and I know that you guys have
been talking about not just

00:47:08.150 --> 00:47:10.120
waiting for performance
management official

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:13.880
conversations, but actually
taking up responsibility

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:16.710
to drive and accelerate
your own learning-- one

00:47:16.710 --> 00:47:20.550
way to do that is not to
go to people and say, hey,

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:22.620
do you have any feedback for me?

00:47:22.620 --> 00:47:24.524
That's a terrible question.

00:47:24.524 --> 00:47:26.940
I mean, nobody knows how to
answer that question, I think.

00:47:26.940 --> 00:47:29.490
And it's not clear how
honest you want them to be.

00:47:29.490 --> 00:47:33.430
Instead, what we suggest
is ask for one thing.

00:47:33.430 --> 00:47:35.720
So say, hey, what's one
thing I'm doing or maybe

00:47:35.720 --> 00:47:38.022
failing to do that's
getting in my own way

00:47:38.022 --> 00:47:39.730
or that's getting in
the way on the team?

00:47:39.730 --> 00:47:41.460
Or ask, what's one
thing I could change

00:47:41.460 --> 00:47:43.100
that would make the
biggest difference?

00:47:43.100 --> 00:47:46.390
You'll get something that's
very specific and more concrete.

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:49.840
And it's clear that you want
them to be honest with you.

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:52.300
And that question can
help you in a bunch

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:54.540
of different
relationships and give you

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:56.097
one thing to work on a time.

00:47:56.097 --> 00:47:57.680
AUDIENCE: So I'm
still kind of hung up

00:47:57.680 --> 00:48:03.220
on when I receive feedback
