00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:05.272
is a personality
trait of myself.

00:48:05.272 --> 00:48:05.980
SHEILA HEEN: Yes.

00:48:05.980 --> 00:48:06.646
AUDIENCE: Right?

00:48:06.646 --> 00:48:09.950
Like oh, maybe you
should think before you

00:48:09.950 --> 00:48:14.407
speak, like that type of stuff.

00:48:14.407 --> 00:48:16.240
DOUGLAS STONE: [INAUDIBLE]
personality trait

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:17.676
of not thinking?

00:48:17.676 --> 00:48:18.800
AUDIENCE: Yeah, no, no, no.

00:48:18.800 --> 00:48:20.091
But like, you know what I mean?

00:48:20.091 --> 00:48:22.220
Like, oh, you need to be
a better listener and all

00:48:22.220 --> 00:48:25.280
these things that I
think I can work on.

00:48:25.280 --> 00:48:29.770
But my personality
just kind of puts me

00:48:29.770 --> 00:48:32.470
kind of on one
side of this scale.

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:33.990
How do you take
feedback that you

00:48:33.990 --> 00:48:37.040
think is just
personal to yourself?

00:48:37.040 --> 00:48:39.554
Like I don't know how much
people can actually change.

00:48:39.554 --> 00:48:41.220
DOUGLAS STONE: Well,
so there's a limit.

00:48:41.220 --> 00:48:43.470
I mean, to take a really
obviously example, if someone

00:48:43.470 --> 00:48:47.300
says you got to work
on how tall you.

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:48.050
You're too tall.

00:48:48.050 --> 00:48:49.020
Or you're too short.

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:49.422
AUDIENCE: Yeah, yeah.

00:48:49.422 --> 00:48:49.730
I'm sitting down.

00:48:49.730 --> 00:48:50.606
That's pretty impressive.

00:48:50.606 --> 00:48:51.814
DOUGLAS STONE: Yeah, exactly.

00:48:51.814 --> 00:48:53.740
So there are things we
literally can't change.

00:48:53.740 --> 00:48:56.073
Then there are things that
are easy, comparatively easy,

00:48:56.073 --> 00:48:59.020
to change like when you get to
work, or where you work from,

00:48:59.020 --> 00:48:59.707
or whatever.

00:48:59.707 --> 00:49:01.540
And then there are
things in the middle that

00:49:01.540 --> 00:49:06.140
are kind of a mix of personality
tendencies and behaviors

00:49:06.140 --> 00:49:08.440
and actions.

00:49:08.440 --> 00:49:13.450
One thing is just to
ask very specifically,

00:49:13.450 --> 00:49:15.296
so how would I do that?

00:49:15.296 --> 00:49:16.670
Or, what does that
look and sound

00:49:16.670 --> 00:49:19.150
like when you say I need
to be more this way?

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:20.430
What does that sound like?

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:25.020
But something you might try is
what we call small experiments.

00:49:25.020 --> 00:49:26.910
So sometimes if
someone says, gee, you

00:49:26.910 --> 00:49:31.260
need to be more outgoing
at work and friendlier.

00:49:31.260 --> 00:49:32.720
And you're thinking, oh, my god.

00:49:32.720 --> 00:49:34.910
I have to change my
whole personality.

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:37.510
I'm going to be working at
Google for the next 40 years.

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:39.740
And I've lived my
whole life this way.

00:49:39.740 --> 00:49:41.710
And now I have to be a
totally different way.

00:49:41.710 --> 00:49:44.220
It can feel overwhelming, right?

00:49:44.220 --> 00:49:46.060
But if you just think about it.

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:51.000
OK, tomorrow, what's one
thing I could try tomorrow?

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:53.770
And if I don't like
the way it feels,

00:49:53.770 --> 00:49:55.500
then I don't have
to keep doing it.

00:49:55.500 --> 00:49:58.060
But if I like it, then
maybe I will keep doing it.

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:02.500
So think of it as very specific,
segmented, just try it.

00:50:02.500 --> 00:50:04.180
If you get some
positive feedback,

00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:05.140
you can keep doing it.

00:50:05.140 --> 00:50:07.680
If you don't and it
doesn't feel comfortable,

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:08.980
you can find another way in.

00:50:08.980 --> 00:50:11.140
SHEILA HEEN: Yeah, modify it.

00:50:11.140 --> 00:50:13.450
One of the things, toward
the back of the book,

00:50:13.450 --> 00:50:16.460
we have five ideas
to get started.

00:50:16.460 --> 00:50:18.590
And there's also a whole
chapter on boundaries,

00:50:18.590 --> 00:50:20.229
how to turn away feedback.

00:50:20.229 --> 00:50:22.020
Because being a good
feedback receiver also

00:50:22.020 --> 00:50:24.353
means knowing how and when
you need to protect yourself.

00:50:24.353 --> 00:50:27.360
If it's a relentless criticism
that's undermining your sense

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:30.211
of self, how do you put
up some boundaries to say,

00:50:30.211 --> 00:50:32.460
you know what, I'm-- I don't
know if I could take that

00:50:32.460 --> 00:50:35.840
feedback, but it's certainly not
something that I put that much

00:50:35.840 --> 00:50:37.440
energy in right now.

00:50:37.440 --> 00:50:39.920
And then how do you talk
to the person about that

00:50:39.920 --> 00:50:42.630
if they're an important
person in your life?

00:50:42.630 --> 00:50:45.160
And then how do you also
mitigate the effect?

00:50:45.160 --> 00:50:48.990
Because just saying, well, too
bad I'm not going to change

00:50:48.990 --> 00:50:51.480
is OK in some cases,
but not in others.

00:50:51.480 --> 00:50:54.020
So then how do we
work around the fact

00:50:54.020 --> 00:50:56.850
that I leave my purse and
wallet and credit cards

00:50:56.850 --> 00:50:58.345
behind most of the time?

00:50:58.345 --> 00:50:59.970
It's a personality
trait I've worked on

00:50:59.970 --> 00:51:02.270
for many, many,
many decades now.

00:51:02.270 --> 00:51:05.030
It's so far, no progress, right?

00:51:05.030 --> 00:51:06.784
But I am doing small
experiments, right?

00:51:06.784 --> 00:51:07.950
Trying to be more organized.

00:51:07.950 --> 00:51:10.034
Stopping to check before
I walk out of a building.

00:51:10.034 --> 00:51:12.324
DOUGLAS STONE: Stapling your
credit card to your pants.

00:51:12.324 --> 00:51:14.890
SHEILA HEEN: Stapling my credit
card, yeah, to my sleeve.

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:15.940
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:15.940 --> 00:51:18.380
I guess it's a question about
that same sense of time.

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:21.090
You said for Sam and Pete,
it worked for a while.

00:51:21.090 --> 00:51:24.837
So how do you have that
upkeep without saying

00:51:24.837 --> 00:51:26.420
that you don't have
faith that they're

00:51:26.420 --> 00:51:27.500
keeping it up themselves?

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:28.492
SHEILA HEEN: I know.

00:51:28.492 --> 00:51:32.516
DOUGLAS STONE: Feedback,
in general, by the way,

00:51:32.516 --> 00:51:34.140
sometimes we think
of it as like, well,

00:51:34.140 --> 00:51:36.348
that's the thing that happens
at the end of the year.

00:51:36.348 --> 00:51:37.880
And I get my evaluation.

00:51:37.880 --> 00:51:39.910
And that's my
feedback conversation.

00:51:39.910 --> 00:51:45.140
So if I have feedback for
someone, it might be March,

00:51:45.140 --> 00:51:47.410
but I'll give it to them
in November or December

00:51:47.410 --> 00:51:50.820
during feedback learning time.

00:51:50.820 --> 00:51:53.500
And there's a way in
which that makes sense.

00:51:53.500 --> 00:51:57.800
Our evaluations come at
a certain time of year.

00:51:57.800 --> 00:52:00.040
And that's useful.

00:52:00.040 --> 00:52:02.370
But other kinds of feedback,
the kind of feedback

00:52:02.370 --> 00:52:05.960
that we would call coaching,
should happen in real time.

00:52:05.960 --> 00:52:09.550
If you're at a
stoplight and the person

00:52:09.550 --> 00:52:14.220
in front of you is not going and
the light has now turned green,

00:52:14.220 --> 00:52:16.920
you wouldn't say to yourself,
well, I'll wait till December

00:52:16.920 --> 00:52:19.570
and I'll honk during
honking season.

00:52:19.570 --> 00:52:22.127
You would honk now because
this is when it's happening.

00:52:22.127 --> 00:52:23.710
So when you have
feedback for someone,

00:52:23.710 --> 00:52:27.680
or you'd like to learn
something or receive feedback,

00:52:27.680 --> 00:52:29.670
if it's coaching,
just do it now.

00:52:29.670 --> 00:52:34.360
In contexts like this, it's
always an ongoing thing.

00:52:34.360 --> 00:52:36.920
It's not a, we had
the conversation once,

00:52:36.920 --> 00:52:39.250
or we had to have a
reinforcement conversation.

00:52:39.250 --> 00:52:40.960
It's going to be
an ever-shifting--

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:42.802
SHEILA HEEN: Yeah, and
it worked for a while

00:52:42.802 --> 00:52:44.510
where they were very
consistent about it.

00:52:44.510 --> 00:52:46.770
And then they would fall
off the wagon, et cetera.

00:52:46.770 --> 00:52:50.630
So the improvement is more
like this than like this.

00:52:50.630 --> 00:52:53.450
And they needed to
expect that, expect

00:52:53.450 --> 00:52:55.700
that we were going to have
to keep coaching each other

00:52:55.700 --> 00:52:57.800
and keep working
pretty hard at it.

00:52:57.800 --> 00:53:00.800
We'll close, by the way, because
I'm getting the time signal.

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:03.130
The hook is coming out.

00:53:03.130 --> 00:53:05.945
We'll close just with one last
piece of research information

00:53:05.945 --> 00:53:08.320
that may be useful to you,
which is that what the studies

00:53:08.320 --> 00:53:11.854
show is that people who seek
out negative feedback at work--

00:53:11.854 --> 00:53:14.270
and in the literature, what
they mean by negative feedback

00:53:14.270 --> 00:53:16.811
is that you're not just going
around fishing for compliments,

00:53:16.811 --> 00:53:20.330
you're actually asking what
could I improve-- those people

00:53:20.330 --> 00:53:22.470
adapt more quickly to new roles.

00:53:22.470 --> 00:53:24.650
They report higher satisfaction.

00:53:24.650 --> 00:53:27.060
And they get higher
performance reviews.

00:53:27.060 --> 00:53:29.920
And so it's not
just that you elicit

00:53:29.920 --> 00:53:33.250
learning that accelerates
your own learning curve.

00:53:33.250 --> 00:53:36.830
It's also that asking for
coaching changes the way

00:53:36.830 --> 00:53:39.040
other people see you.

00:53:39.040 --> 00:53:41.420
And so it can be a powerful
tool to have in your toolbox.

00:53:41.420 --> 00:53:43.920
And then you don't have to wait
around for the perfect giver

00:53:43.920 --> 00:53:46.295
because mostly our lives are
populated by everybody else.

00:53:46.295 --> 00:53:49.180
So we got to learn
how to learn something

00:53:49.180 --> 00:53:52.902
from all kinds of givers who
sometimes are off base, unfair.

00:53:52.902 --> 00:53:53.860
They deliver it poorly.

00:53:53.860 --> 00:53:57.520
And yet we're going to find
something valuable in it.

00:53:57.520 --> 00:54:01.220
We're happy to stick around to
answer questions, et cetera.

